<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Win and Lose Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Ends the mission successfully or unsuccessfully when the configured trigger logic fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Win and Lose Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Win</Bold> and <Bold>Lose</Bold> Event Points are used to end the mission. A Win Event
        Point completes the mission successfully. A Lose Event Point fails the mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        These Event Points are simple in terms of their own fields. Like other Event Points, they
        have common properties such as index number, type, letter group, colour, position, trigger
        settings, and listening mode. However, for Win and Lose Event Points, the position normally
        does not matter in gameplay.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The important part is the <Bold>trigger logic</Bold>. A Win or Lose Event Point matters when
        it becomes active. The mission result is controlled by whatever trigger causes it to fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical concept:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Win and Lose Event Points are trigger-driven. Their map position is mostly for editor organisation.
                    What matters is the condition that activates them.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- ADDING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding Win or Lose Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add a mission ending Event Point, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select
        the appropriate Win or Lose Event Point type, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The editor opens the normal <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window. There are no meaningful
        type-specific properties to configure for these endpoints. Configure the common properties
        and, most importantly, the trigger settings.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- COMMON PROPERTIES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Win and Lose Event Points use the standard Event Point common properties:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Index number</Bold> — automatic Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Type</Bold> — automatic Event Point type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Letter Group</Bold> — useful for organisation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Colour</Bold> — useful for visually separating mission-ending logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Position</Bold> — normally not important for gameplay, but useful for editor readability.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Trigger settings</Bold> — the condition that makes the mission win or lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening mode</Bold> — controls how the Event Point listens for or reacts to its trigger.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Because position is usually irrelevant, you can place Win and Lose Event Points somewhere
        convenient in the editor. Many mission authors place ending logic near the area it relates to,
        or group all ending logic in a clear corner of the map for easy inspection.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Organisation tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Use a consistent colour or letter group for mission-ending logic. For example, put all Win/Lose Event Points in one group so they are easy to find later.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TYPE-SPECIFIC PROPERTIES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Type-Specific Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Win and Lose Event Points have no meaningful type-specific configuration. Their purpose is
        simply to end the mission when activated.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This means that the help, design, and testing focus should be on the Event Point’s trigger
        condition. If the trigger never fires, the mission will never win or lose through that Event
        Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Simple rule:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Win means mission success. Lose means mission failure. The trigger decides when either result happens.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TRIGGER LOGIC -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger logic is the entire purpose of Win and Lose Event Points. They can be triggered by
        simple conditions, or by complex chains of Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Simple Trigger Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A simple mission can end directly from one condition. For example:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Person Arrested → Win</Bold> — the mission is completed when a specific NPC is arrested.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Person Dead → Lose</Bold> — the mission fails if a protected person dies.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Player Enters Radius → Win</Bold> — the mission completes when the player reaches an extraction point.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Timer / Countdown Expires → Lose</Bold> — the mission fails when time runs out.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Item Held / Specific Item Held → Win</Bold> — the mission completes when the player has recovered a required item.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For simple conditions involving a specific NPC or object, make sure the relevant
        <Bold>Target EP</Bold>, <Bold>Dependency EP</Bold>, or reference field points to the correct
        Event Point number.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Reference warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    If the Win or Lose trigger depends on a specific person, item, object, timer, or previous Event Point,
                    the reference must point to the correct Event Point number. A wrong reference can make the mission impossible to finish or impossible to fail.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- COMPLEX LOGIC -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Complex Win and Lose Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Win and Lose Event Points can also be triggered by chains of other Event Points. This is how
        more advanced missions create multi-part objectives, optional routes, conditional outcomes,
        and fail states.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A common pattern is to use <Bold>Simple Waypoints</Bold> or other intermediate Event Points
        as logic nodes. These can be connected with <Bold>Dependency</Bold>,
        <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold>, and <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> triggers.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_boolean_logic.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Boolean AND
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold> when multiple conditions must all be true before the mission
        should win or lose.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Example:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Suspect arrested AND evidence collected -> Win
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Boolean OR
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> when any one of several conditions should be enough to cause the
        mission to win or lose.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Example:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Hostage killed OR player leaves area OR timer expires -> Lose
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Dependency Chains
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when a Win or Lose Event Point should activate after another
        Event Point has fired. This lets you build readable chains where intermediate Event Points
        represent mission progress.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Example:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Player reaches extraction -> Simple Waypoint activates -> Win Event Point fires
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- MULTIPLE WIN/LOSE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Multiple Win and Lose Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A mission can have <Bold>multiple Win Event Points</Bold> and <Bold>multiple Lose Event Points</Bold>.
        This is normal and often useful.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each Win or Lose Event Point can represent a different ending condition. For example, one
        Win Event Point might complete the mission when the target is arrested, while another might
        complete the mission when the player escapes with an item. Similarly, one Lose Event Point
        might fail the mission if a protected NPC dies, while another fails the mission if time runs
        out.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_win_lose_multiple_endings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Design tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Multiple Win and Lose Event Points are useful when a mission has several valid success paths or several independent fail states.
                    Keep them clearly labelled by group, colour, or placement so they remain readable.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example Multiple Win Conditions
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Arrest the target → Win.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Recover the evidence and reach the extraction point → Win.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Disable the bomb before the timer expires → Win.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Complete all required objectives using Boolean AND → Win.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example Multiple Lose Conditions
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Protected NPC dies → Lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player kills the wrong person → Lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Timer expires → Lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters a forbidden zone → Lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Mission-critical object is destroyed → Lose.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PRACTICAL EXAMPLES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Simple Arrest Mission</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a Win Event Point. Set its trigger to <Bold>Person Arrested</Bold> and reference the
        target NPC. When that NPC is arrested, the mission ends successfully.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Protect the Witness</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a Lose Event Point. Set its trigger to <Bold>Person Dead</Bold>,
        <Bold>Killed or Arrested</Bold>, or another appropriate person-state trigger and reference
        the witness NPC. If the witness dies, the mission fails.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Collect Evidence and Escape</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use one Event Point to detect evidence collection and another to detect reaching the escape
        point. Connect them with <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold>, then trigger a Win Event Point from the
        result.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Timed Failure</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use a timer or countdown Event Point. If the timer completes before the objective is
        satisfied, trigger a Lose Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Multiple Failure States</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Add separate Lose Event Points for different fail states, such as the target escaping, a
        civilian dying, time running out, or the player entering a restricted area.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- WORKFLOW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Win Event Point Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what condition should complete the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create any required supporting Event Points first, such as target NPCs, items, timers, counters, or waypoints.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> and select the Win Event Point type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a clear group and colour for mission-ending logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place it somewhere readable in the editor. Exact position is normally not gameplay-critical.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger condition that should cause mission success.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the trigger references another Event Point, set the reference to the correct Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Lose Event Point Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what condition should fail the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create any required supporting Event Points first, such as protected NPCs, timers, zones, objects, or counters.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> and select the Lose Event Point type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a clear group and colour for mission-ending logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place it somewhere readable in the editor. Exact position is normally not gameplay-critical.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger condition that should cause mission failure.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the trigger references another Event Point, set the reference to the correct Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the failure condition.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TESTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Testing Win and Lose Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Always test both success and failure paths. It is easy to create a mission that can be won
        but not failed, or failed but not won, because one trigger reference is wrong or one
        dependency chain never becomes true.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test every Win condition individually.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test every Lose condition individually.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test what happens if multiple ending conditions become true close together.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test Boolean AND chains by satisfying only one side, then both sides.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test Boolean OR chains by satisfying each possible branch separately.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test failure paths before and after mission objectives are completed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TROUBLESHOOTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Troubleshooting
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The mission never wins</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Win Event Point exists.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the trigger condition is firing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm any Target EP, Dependency EP, or Boolean reference points to the correct Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using Boolean AND, confirm all required conditions are becoming true.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Temporarily test with a simpler trigger to confirm the Win Event Point itself works.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The mission never loses</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Lose Event Point exists.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the fail condition actually occurs in game.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm any referenced NPC, timer, object, zone, or dependency is the correct Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the Lose condition directly before combining it into complex logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The mission ends too early</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether the Win or Lose Event Point uses <Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold> by mistake.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether a dependency is already active from mission start.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check Boolean OR logic, because any true branch can trigger the ending.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether multiple Win or Lose Event Points exist and another one is firing first.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The wrong ending happens</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Search the mission for all Win and Lose Event Points.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check each ending trigger separately.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm no old test Win/Lose Event Point is still active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm Boolean references and dependencies point to the intended Event Points.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Win and Lose Event Points are simple, but mission endings can become complex.
                    Keep the trigger chains readable, test every ending path, and remember that multiple Win and Lose Event Points can exist in one mission.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>